[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1959-afc-youth-championship] The **1959 AFC Youth Championship** was held in Kuala Lumpur, Federation of Malaya.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1959-afc-youth-championship] It was the first time the tournament was organised.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1959-afc-youth-championship] Four winners moved to group A and played for the championship.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1959-afc-youth-championship] Five other teams moved to consolation group B.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1959-afc-youth-championship] Philippines and Thailand had to play in a preliminary round.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1960-afc-youth-championship] The **1960 AFC Youth Championship** was held in Malaya.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1970-afc-youth-championship] The **1970 AFC Youth Championship** was held in Manila, Philippines.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1974-afc-youth-championship] The **1974 AFC Youth Championship** was held in Bangkok, Thailand.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1974-afc-youth-championship] India and Iran shared the title after the final ended in a **2**–**2** Draw.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1974-afc-youth-championship] This was also the last tournament South Vietnam participated, one year later on 30 April 1975 South Vietnam was annexed by North Vietnam.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1977-afc-youth-championship] The **1977 AFC Youth Championship** was held between April 15 and April 28 in Iran.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1977-afc-youth-championship] It was won by Iraq 4-3 over Iran in Aryamehr Stadium in Tehran in front of 100,000 spectators.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1977-afc-youth-championship] Both teams qualified for 1977 FIFA World Youth Championship.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1977-afc-youth-championship] The two best performing teams qualified for the 1977 FIFA World Youth Championship.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1977-fifa-world-youth-championship] The **1977 FIFA World Youth Championship** was the inaugural staging of the FIFA World Youth Championship, hosted by Tunisia from 27 June to 10 July 1977, in three venues — Tunis, Sousse and Sfax.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1977-fifa-world-youth-championship] The 28 matches played were the smallest number in tournament history.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1977-fifa-world-youth-championship] The USSR U20s defeated Mexico U20s in a penalty shootout, in the final held at Tunis's Stade El Menzah.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1977-fifa-world-youth-championship] The Tournament Committee was chaired by FIFA Vice-President Harry Cavan, who had spearheaded the creation of the World Youth Championship.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1977-fifa-world-youth-championship] The group winners advanced directly to the semifinals.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1977-fifa-world-youth-championship] Guina of Brazil won the Golden Boot award for scoring four goals.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1977-fifa-world-youth-championship] In total, 70 goals were scored by 49 different players, with none of them credited as own goal.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1978-afc-youth-championship] The **1978 AFC Youth Championship** was held in Dhaka, Bangladesh from 5 October to 28 October 1978.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1978-afc-youth-championship] It also served as qualification for the 1979 FIFA World Youth Championship.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/1978-afc-youth-championship] The following teams qualified for the 1979 FIFA World Youth Championship.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/china-national-under-20-football-team] The **China national under-20 football team**, also known as the **China Youth Team** (国青队), represents the People's Republic of China in international football competitions in the FIFA U-20 World Cup and the AFC U-20 Asian Cup, as well as any other under-20 international football tournaments.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/china-national-under-20-football-team] It is governed by the Chinese Football Association (CFA).
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/china-national-under-20-football-team] In 2017, the under-20 team began playing in the Regionalliga Südwest, a fourth-division German league, as part of an agreement between the two countries.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/china-national-under-20-football-team] The team would play friendly matches to fill in for the missing 20th club in the league's schedule.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/china-national-under-20-football-team] During the team's match on 17 November against TSV Schott Mainz, the display of a Tibetan flag led to the team walking off in protest.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/china-national-under-20-football-team] In the aftermath, all upcoming friendly matches were cancelled.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/china-national-under-20-football-team] On 28 September 2018, China U-19 Yellow (B team) was organised as support for the national under-20 football team.
[src:china-national-under-20-football-team/china-national-under-20-football-team] The following is a list of match results in the last 24 months, as well as any future matches that have been scheduled.
